  abstract class Ascription {
    +getId(): String
    +getRevisionId(): String
    +getArchetype(): Archetype
    +getDefinition(): String
    +getVersion(): String
    +getStatus(): AscriptionStatus
    +getStatusTransitions(): AscriptionStatusTransition[]
  }

  note bottom of Ascription
    **Ascription** — Abstract base for all GSM definitions.

    **Concept Semantics**:

    - An Ascription is the act of assigning normative structure to an identity.
      Every structural constituent of a Structure (Mechanism, Interaction,
      Interface), the Structure itself, Archetypes, Directives, and Norms
      are Ascriptions.
    - `id` is the stable identity of the thing being defined. Multiple
      definitions (revisions) share the same `id` — each is a distinct
      definition snapshot of the same thing. `revisionId` uniquely identifies
      each revision row. Both `id` and `revisionId` are **UUIDv7**
      (RFC 9562): time-sortable (Unix epoch ms + random), monotonically
      increasing, and B-tree friendly. At most one in-effect definition per
      `id` (status = ACTIVE or DEPRECATED).
    - Every Ascription is representable as Archetype-typed information
      for Mechanisms. This enables systemic recursion — reflexive Mechanisms
      inspect and transform the Structure's own Ascriptions.
    - Multiple revisions of the same `id` can coexist in non-terminal
      states (DRAFT, PROPOSED) concurrently — the creative/authoring phase is
      open. Governance converges at approval: approving any one revision
      auto-rejects all other non-terminal sibling revisions for that
      `id`.
    - `version` tracks governance-validated definition lineage (gapless). A
      DRAFT that is ABANDONED, or a PROPOSED revision that is REJECTED or
      never APPROVED, never consumes a `version` number.
    - `statusTransitions` provides a complete governance audit trail: who
      changed the status, when, and why.
    - An Ascription **revision** is an **immutable snapshot**. Any change
      to the definition content MUST be expressed by authoring a new revision
      (new `revisionId`) for the same `id`. The only
      permitted in-place evolution of a revision row is the append-only growth
      of its `statusTransitions` audit trail.
    - **Governance convergence pattern**: the creative phase allows concurrent
      authoring (multiple DRAFT and PROPOSED revisions for the same
      `id`). The governance decision phase converges: approving one
      revision auto-terminates all siblings (DRAFT siblings → ABANDONED,
      PROPOSED siblings → REJECTED). This separates creative freedom
      (author many alternatives) from governance rigor (exactly one winner).
      After convergence, new revisions can be authored to start a new creative
      cycle.
    - **Terminality of ABANDONED and REJECTED**: ABANDONED and REJECTED are
      both terminal states. Once a revision reaches either state, it cannot be
      reopened or set back to any prior status. ABANDONED applies to DRAFTs
      (never submitted for review); REJECTED applies to PROPOSED revisions
      (denied by governance). If a new creative cycle is needed, author a new
      revision (new `revisionId`, fresh DRAFT) — do not resurrect a
      terminated revision. This preserves governance convergence and a clean
      audit trail.

    **Attribute Semantics**:

    - `id`: stable identity of the thing being defined (UUIDv7). Shared
      across all revisions/definitions of the same referent. Immutable once
      assigned. Time-sortable — encodes creation timestamp.
    - `revisionId`: globally unique identity of THIS revision (UUIDv7,
      unique per revision row). Time-sortable — encodes creation
      timestamp. The creation timestamp is derivable from the UUIDv7 value.
    - `archetype`: reference to the Archetype that types this definition,
      constraining its definition content and providing domain semantics.
    - `definition`: JSON-serializable payload applied to the element.
      Carries the concrete, version-specific content whose structure is
      constrained by the Archetype schema (extension via `allOf`).
      The `definition` payload is the fast-changing layer (A) of the
      DNA — element-level configuration, parameters, and operational metadata.
    - `version`: numerical string assigned only upon APPROVED transition.
      Monotonically increasing within the APPROVED lineage for a given
      `id`. Null/unset until approved. Governance-meaningful — represents
      the validated definition lineage (gapless). A definition earns a version
      when governance accepts it as a definition; whether it is later applied
      (ACTIVE) is a downstream realization concern, not a definitional one.
    - `status`: lifecycle state (cf. AscriptionStatus).
      Denormalized/cache field derived from the latest
      `statusTransitions[*].postStatus`.
    - `statusTransitions`: ordered list of AscriptionStatusTransition
      records capturing every lifecycle state change. Append-only — transitions
      are never modified or deleted (cf. AscriptionStatusTransition).

    **Validation Rules**:

    - `definition` MUST validate against the JSON Schema referenced by
      `archetype.definition.schemaUri`.

    **Assignment Rules**:

    - When creating a new definition revision, reuse the same `id`.
    - Immutability (revision snapshot): once a revision row is created, `id`,
      `revisionId`, `archetype`, and `definition` MUST NOT be modified in place.
    - Once `version` is assigned at APPROVED transition, it MUST NOT be
      modified.
    - `version` is auto-assigned by the definition-manager at APPROVED
      transition — never set manually.
    - Until APPROVED transition, `version` MUST be null.
    - `version` MUST be monotonically increasing within the APPROVED lineage for
      each `id`.

    **State Rules**:

    - See `gsm-ascription-lifecycle` state machine diagram
      for valid transitions, preconditions, cascades,
      and audit-log invariants.
    - At most one in-effect definition per `id` (status = ACTIVE or
      DEPRECATED).

    **Derivation Rules**:

    - An element is "in effect" in production when its definition status is
      ACTIVE or DEPRECATED for its `id`.
    - `getId()` → column `id` (UUIDv7)
    - `getRevisionId()` → column `revision_id` (UUIDv7)
    - `getArchetype()` → column `archetype_id` → resolves Archetype
    - `getDefinition()` → column `definition` (JSONB)
    - `getVersion()` → column `version`
    - `getStatus()` → column `status` (denormalized from latest transition)
    - `getStatusTransitions()` → composition (AscriptionStatusTransition rows
      for this `revision_id`)
  end note

  Ascription "0..*" --> "1" Archetype : has
  Ascription "1" *--> "1..*" AscriptionStatusTransition : has

  class AscriptionStatusTransition {
    +getId(): String
    +getRevisionId(): String
    +getPreStatus(): AscriptionStatus
    +getPostStatus(): AscriptionStatus
  }

  note bottom of AscriptionStatusTransition
    **AscriptionStatusTransition** — Governance audit record.

    **Concept Semantics**:

    - Immutable record of a single lifecycle state change on an
      Ascription.
    - Lifecycle-coupled to the owning Ascription (destroying the
      definition destroys its transitions).
    - The ordered collection of transitions constitutes the complete governance
      audit trail for a definition.
    - The initial entry captures creation (preStatus = null, postStatus =
      DRAFT).

    **Attribute Semantics**:

    - `id`: unique identity of THIS transition record (UUIDv7, RFC 9562).
      Time-sortable — the transition timestamp is embedded in the UUIDv7
      value and derivable from it. This eliminates a separate `datetime`
      field: the moment the transition is created IS the moment it occurred,
      encoded in `id`.
    - `revisionId`: reference to the owning Ascription's `revisionId` (the
      specific revision row, not `id`). Immutable once assigned.
    - `preStatus`: the status before the transition. Null for the initial
      creation entry.
    - `postStatus`: the status after the transition.

    **Validation Rules**:

    - `postStatus` MUST NOT be null.
    - `revisionId` MUST NOT be null.
    - `revisionId` MUST reference an existing Ascription `revisionId`.

    **Assignment Rules**:

    - `id` is assigned at creation time and MUST NOT be modified.

    **State Rules**:

    - See `gsm-ascription-lifecycle` state machine diagram
      for valid transitions, preconditions, cascades,
      and audit-log invariants.

    **Derivation Rules**:

    - The transition timestamp is derived from `id` (UUIDv7 embedded
      Unix epoch ms).
    - Governance analytics (time-in-status, approval latency, rejection rates)
      can be derived from the transition chain.
    - `getId()` → column `id` (UUIDv7)
    - `getRevisionId()` → column `revision_id` (FK to Ascription)
    - `getPreStatus()` → column `pre_status`
    - `getPostStatus()` → column `post_status`
  end note

  AscriptionStatusTransition "1..*" --> "1" Ascription : belongsTo

  enum AscriptionStatus {
    DRAFT
    PROPOSED
    APPROVED
    ACTIVE
    SUSPENDED
    DEPRECATED
    RETIRED
    ABANDONED
    REJECTED
  }

  note bottom of AscriptionStatus
    **AscriptionStatus** — Lifecycle stages.

    **Attribute Semantics**:

    - `DRAFT`: initial creation state. Editable authoring state; not in effect
      at runtime.
    - `PROPOSED`: submitted for review. Under governance review; not in effect
      at runtime.
    - `APPROVED`: accepted as a valid definition; `version` assigned. Awaiting
      activation; not yet in effect.
    - `ACTIVE`: in effect at runtime.
    - `SUSPENDED`: temporarily not in effect, retains lineage; may be
      reactivated.
    - `DEPRECATED`: in effect but scheduled for retirement; emits warnings on
      new references.
    - `RETIRED`: permanently not in effect; preserved for historical
      traceability (terminal).
    - `ABANDONED`: author-initiated termination of a DRAFT; the revision was
      never submitted for governance review. A new creative cycle requires
      authoring a new revision (terminal).
    - `REJECTED`: denied by governance; not in effect. Only reachable from
      PROPOSED. A new creative cycle requires authoring a new revision
      (terminal).

    **State Rules**:

    - See `gsm-ascription-lifecycle` state machine diagram
      for valid transitions, preconditions, cascades,
      and audit-log invariants.

    **Usage Rules**:

    - Before activating, verify no conflicting ACTIVE definition exists for the
      same `id`.
  end note

  ' ============================================================
  ' STRUCTURE
  ' ============================================================

  class Structure {
    +getPurpose(): String
    +getMechanisms(): Mechanism[]
    +getInterfaces(): Interface[]
  }

  note bottom of Structure
    **Structure** — The foundational aggregate.

    **Concept Semantics**:

    - The assembly of Elements constituting a Structure is **intentional**: it
      is never accidental authoring. A Structure's element set and topology
      exist **for a purpose** and are the product of governance.
    - **Governing Structure (governance relation)**: a Structure `G` governs a
      Structure `S` when `G` produces governance DNA (Directives/Norms)
      targeting `S` (by referencing `StructureArchetype.purpose`, and by
      operationalizing those Directives as Norms constraining in-scope
      Elements). This is how
      inter-Structure governance is expressed in GSM: not by containment, but by
      DNA targeting (de-facto) governed Elements.
    - **Formalization**: `G` governs `S` **iff** (a) there exists at least one
      Directive authored/owned by `G` whose `purpose` field references
      `StructureArchetype.purpose`, and
      (b) over time, those Directives are operationalized by one or more Norms
      authored/owned by `G` that constrain (target) in-scope Elements of `S`.
    - **Purpose is owned by governance**: `StructureArchetype.purpose` is the
      Structure's identity field, but it is not self-declared — it is a
      **governed outcome**. A governing Structure confers purpose by producing
      Directives that address it. Purpose without governance addressing is an
      orphan: a Structure exists *because* a governing Structure decided this
      aggregate of Mechanisms should exist for this reason. This reflects the
      cybernetic principle that identity is conferred by the meta-system, not
      intrinsic to the system itself.
    - No sub-structures, no containment hierarchy. Governance between Structures
      is expressed through DNA targeting governed Elements — not through
      illusional hierarchical nesting.

    **Attribute Semantics**:

    - `purpose`: the Structure's raison d'être. This IS the Structure's
      identity/name. Globally unique — serves as both identity discriminator
      and governance address. Directives reference the purpose via their
      `purpose` field.
    - `mechanisms`: the set of Mechanisms belonging to this Structure. A
      Mechanism belongs to exactly one Structure.
    - `interfaces`: the set of Interfaces belonging to this Structure. An
      Interface belongs to exactly one Structure.

    **Validation Rules**:

    - `StructureArchetype.purpose` MUST be non-empty (enforced by base schema).
    - `StructureArchetype.purpose` MUST be globally unique among in-effect
      (ACTIVE or DEPRECATED) Structure Ascriptions.

    **State Rules**:

    - See `gsm-ascription-lifecycle` state machine diagram
      for valid transitions, preconditions, cascades,
      and audit-log invariants.
    - The definition-manager MUST reject activation of a Structure whose purpose
      duplicates an already in-effect Structure's purpose.

    **Derivation Rules**:

    - `getPurpose()` → `definition.purpose`
    - `getMechanisms()` → reverse lookup (Mechanisms whose `definition.structure` = this.id)
    - `getInterfaces()` → derived (Interfaces whose ports belong to this Structure's Mechanisms)
  end note

  Structure --|> Ascription
  Structure "1" *--> "0..*" Mechanism : has
  Structure "1" *--> "0..*" Interface : has

  ' ============================================================
  ' MECHANISM
  ' ============================================================

  class Mechanism {
    +getStructure(): Structure
    +getFunction(): String
    +getRule(): String
    +getRuleLanguage(): String
    +getEffectors(): Effector[]
    +getReceptors(): Receptor[]
  }

  note bottom of Mechanism
    **Mechanism** — Logical causal unit.

    **Concept Semantics**:

    - Composite of processing logic (`MechanismArchetype.rule`) and its
      I/O ports (Effectors and Receptors).
    - Effectors/Receptors are **derived ports**: they are not authored as part
      of the Mechanism's Ascription schema. The definition-manager derives and
      creates them from `MechanismArchetype.rule` (STARLARK) as part of
      definition compilation.
    - Ports do not exist independently — destroying a Mechanism destroys its
      parts. This IS internal composition (lifecycle coupling, existential
      dependency) — distinct from the inter-structure "composition" that GSM
      eliminates. A port without a processor has no causal autonomy.
    - When `MechanismArchetype.rule` targets the owning Structure's
      Elements, it is reflexive. Reflexive Mechanisms produce governance DNA
      (Directives, Norms), making the Structure a *System*.
    - At least 1 Effector (1..*) and at least 1 Receptor (1..*).

    **Attribute Semantics**:

    - `structure`: the Structure this Mechanism constitutes.
    - `function`: capability label describing what the Mechanism does
      (e.g., "UserValidation", "PaymentRouting", "OrderTransformation").
      MUST be unique within the owning Structure's scope — two Mechanisms
      in the same Structure cannot share the same function. Represents
      teleological decomposition: what capacity this Mechanism contributes
      to the Structure's purpose.
    - `rule`: Starlark source code defining the Mechanism's behavioral
      logic. This IS the compilable logical atom — the single source of
      truth for imperative behavioral definitions. The definition-manager
      auto-derives the Mechanism's Effectors and Receptors from the rule
      body's AST (see Derivation Rules for the full derivation table).
    - `ruleLanguage`: the language of the `rule` code. Supported values:
      "STARLARK".

    **Validation Rules**:

    - `MechanismArchetype.rule` MUST be syntactically valid Starlark
      (parseable by the Starlark parser).
    - `MechanismArchetype.rule` MUST begin with exactly one
      `on("...")` call as its first executable statement.
    - The `on()` argument MUST be a string literal resolving to a defined
      Archetype in the governed scope.
    - String literals in `sys.*` calls (first argument = archetype name)
      MUST be string literals (enables static analysis and port
      auto-derivation).
    - String literals in `sys.*` calls MUST resolve to declared Archetypes
      in the governed scope.
    - Dict literals in `sys.emit/create/modify` SHOULD conform to the
      target Archetype schema (best-effort for dynamic values).
    - Only `sys`, injected host functions (`on`, `now`, `uuid7`,
      `fullmatch`, `search`), and Starlark built-ins are allowed globals.
      Any other global → error.
    - No `load()` statements.
    - Execution budget: configurable max steps (default 100k).
    - `MechanismArchetype.ruleLanguage` MUST be a supported value
      (enforced by base schema enum).
    - `MechanismArchetype.function` MUST be non-empty.
    - `MechanismArchetype.function` MUST be unique among all in-effect
      Mechanisms belonging to the same Structure.
    - MUST have at least 1 Effector (guaranteed if `on()` is present).
    - MUST have at least 1 Receptor (guaranteed if at least one `sys.*`
      output call is present).

    **State Rules**:

    - See `gsm-ascription-lifecycle` state machine diagram
      for valid transitions, preconditions, cascades,
      and audit-log invariants.
    - Mechanism.function: NOT unique — not globally, not within Structure.
    - The definition-manager MUST reject activation of a Mechanism whose
      function duplicates an already in-effect sibling Mechanism within the same
      Structure.

    **Relational Consistency Rules**:

    **Derivation Rules**:

    - The Structure reference is derived from the Mechanism's Archetype
      (`structure`).
    - *Receptor derivation (inputs)*
      - `on("ArchetypeName")` — MUST be the first executable statement.
        Declares the triggering Archetype and returns its payload.
        Auto-derives a Receptor typed by the named Archetype.
      - Return-value assignment of a `sys.*` mutation call (see below)
        auto-derives an additional Receptor (feedback / closed-loop).
    - *Effector derivation (outputs)*
      - `sys.emit("ArchetypeName", data)` — emits data typed by the
        named Archetype. Auto-derives an Effector.
      - `sys.emit("ArchetypeName", data, response="RespArchetype")` —
        emits with a synchronous response expectation. Auto-derives an
        Effector (for the emit) and a Receptor (for the response).
      - `sys.create("ArchetypeName", data)` — creates a state object.
        Auto-derives an Effector.
      - `sys.modify("ArchetypeName", filter, data)` — modifies state
        object(s). Auto-derives an Effector.
      - `sys.delete("ArchetypeName", filter)` — deletes state
        object(s). Auto-derives an Effector.
      - `sys.acquire("ArchetypeName", filter)` — reads/acquires state
        object(s). Auto-derives an Effector.
    - `getStructure()` → `definition.structure` → resolves Structure
    - `getFunction()` → `definition.function`
    - `getRule()` → `definition.rule`
    - `getRuleLanguage()` → `definition.ruleLanguage`
    - `getEffectors()` → derived ports (auto-derived from `definition.rule` AST)
    - `getReceptors()` → derived ports (auto-derived from `definition.rule` AST)

    **Usage Rules**:

      - **Rule API contract (STARLARK)**
        The rule body executes within a sandboxed Starlark environment
        that exposes exactly: the `sys` namespace, injected host functions
        (`on`, `now`, `uuid7`, `fullmatch`, `search`), and Starlark
        built-ins. No other globals are permitted.
        - *`sys` namespace*
          - `sys.id` — read-only property: the Mechanism's `id`.
        - *Closed-loop vs open-loop pattern*
          - `var = sys.create(...)` (assigned) → **closed-loop**: the DM
            auto-derives a feedback Receptor, enabling verification.
          - `sys.create(...)` (unassigned) → **open-loop** / fire-and-forget:
            no feedback Receptor is derived.
          - Same pattern applies to `sys.modify`, `sys.delete`,
            `sys.acquire`.
        - *Injected host functions*
          - `on(archetype)` — event trigger declaration (see above).
          - `now()` → ISO 8601 timestamp.
          - `uuid7()` → UUIDv7 string (RFC 9562, time-sortable).
          - `fullmatch(pattern, string)` → boolean (full regex match).
          - `search(pattern, string)` → first regex match or None.
  end note

  Mechanism --|> Ascription
  Mechanism "0..*" --> "1" Structure : constitutes
  Mechanism "1" *--> "1..*" Effector : has
  Mechanism "1" *--> "1..*" Receptor : has

  ' ============================================================
  ' EFFECTOR
  ' ============================================================

  class Effector {
    +getMechanism(): Mechanism
    +getArchetype(): Archetype
    +getInterface(): Interface
  }

  note bottom of Effector
    **Effector** — Output port of a Mechanism.

    **Concept Semantics**:

    - Declares the type of information the Mechanism emits, by referencing an
      Archetype. The Archetype's schema determines the structure of the emitted
      data.
    - Interactions originate from Effectors.
    - Represents a mechanism's capability to produce an *effect*.
    - Effectors are *ports*; they do not carry values at the GSM level. Values
      exist in runtime instances.

    **Attribute Semantics**:

    - `mechanism`: the composite Mechanism. An Effector cannot exist without a
      Mechanism.
    - `archetype`: the Archetype that types and constrains the
      effector's output. Note: this is the **port data archetype** (from
      `definition.archetype`), distinct from the Ascription-level
      `archetype` (envelope column) that types the Effector Ascription
      itself as EffectorArchetype.
    - `interface`: optional reference to an Interface that exposes this Effector
      for inter-Structure coupling. If null, the Effector is private to its
      Structure.

    **Validation Rules**:

    - `mechanism` reference MUST NOT be null.
    - `archetype` reference MUST NOT be null.
    - `interface` reference, if present, MUST reference an Interface that
      belongs to the same Structure as the Mechanism.

    **State Rules**:

    - See `gsm-ascription-lifecycle` state machine diagram
      for valid transitions, preconditions, cascades,
      and audit-log invariants.

    **Derivation Rules**:

    - `getMechanism()` → `definition.mechanism` → resolves Mechanism
    - `getArchetype()` → `definition.archetype` → resolves Archetype
    - `getInterface()` → `definition.interface` → resolves Interface (nullable)
  end note

  Effector --|> Ascription
  Effector "1..*" --> "1" Mechanism : constitutes
  Effector "0..*" --> "1" Archetype : produces
  Effector "0..*" --> "0..1" Interface : exposedBy

  ' ============================================================
  ' RECEPTOR
  ' ============================================================

  class Receptor {
    +getMechanism(): Mechanism
    +getArchetype(): Archetype
    +getInterface(): Interface
  }

  note bottom of Receptor
    **Receptor** — Input port of a Mechanism.

    **Concept Semantics**:

    - Declares the type of information the Mechanism receives, by referencing an
      Archetype. The Archetype's schema determines the structure of the
      received data.
    - Interactions terminate at Receptors.
    - Received Archetype-typed instances represent a *cause* for the mechanism
      to operate.
    - Receptors are *ports*; they do not carry values at the GSM level. Values
      exist in runtime instances.

    **Attribute Semantics**:

    - `mechanism`: the composite Mechanism. A Receptor cannot exist without a
      Mechanism.
    - `archetype`: the Archetype that types and constrains the
      receptor's input. Note: this is the **port data archetype** (from
      `definition.archetype`), distinct from the Ascription-level
      `archetype` (envelope column) that types the Receptor Ascription
      itself as ReceptorArchetype.
    - `interface`: optional reference to an Interface that exposes this Receptor
      for inter-Structure coupling. If null, the Receptor is private to its
      Structure.

    **Validation Rules**:

    - `mechanism` reference MUST NOT be null.
    - `archetype` reference MUST NOT be null.
    - `interface` reference, if present, MUST reference an Interface that
      belongs to the same Structure as the Mechanism.

    **State Rules**:

    - See `gsm-ascription-lifecycle` state machine diagram
      for valid transitions, preconditions, cascades,
      and audit-log invariants.

    **Derivation Rules**:

    - `getMechanism()` → `definition.mechanism` → resolves Mechanism
    - `getArchetype()` → `definition.archetype` → resolves Archetype
    - `getInterface()` → `definition.interface` → resolves Interface (nullable)
  end note

  Receptor --|> Ascription
  Receptor "1..*" --> "1" Mechanism : constitutes
  Receptor "0..*" --> "1" Archetype : consumes
  Receptor "0..*" --> "0..1" Interface : exposedBy

  ' ============================================================
  ' INTERACTION
  ' ============================================================

  class Interaction {
    +getEffector(): Effector
    +getReceptor(): Receptor
  }

  note bottom of Interaction
    **Interaction** — Causal coupling between Mechanisms.

    **Concept Semantics**:

    - An **atomic causal coupling** from a producing effector to a
      receiving receptor — the primitive of causality in the system.
    - Connects an Effector of one Mechanism to a Receptor of another or the
      same Mechanism.
    - An Interaction may connect an Effector and a Receptor belonging to
      different Structures.
    - When coupling crosses Structures, the participating ports is
      exposed by Interfaces of their respective Structures (Interface is the
      exposure manifest; Interaction is the causal binding).
    - All causality is Interaction-mediated — no shared state at the structural
      level.
    - Channel properties (environmental constraints, capacity, ...) are
      expressed as governance Norms targeting the Interaction (physical laws
      are Norms of the Universal Structure).

    **Attribute Semantics**:

    - `effector`: The emitting endpoint producing an event instance.
    - `receptor`: The receiving endpoint consuming an event instance.

    **Validation Rules**:

    - `InteractionArchetype.effector` MUST NOT be null.
    - `InteractionArchetype.receptor` MUST NOT be null.
    - `effector.archetype` MUST be schema-compatible with
      `receptor.archetype`.

    **State Rules**:

    - See `gsm-ascription-lifecycle` state machine diagram
      for valid transitions, preconditions, cascades,
      and audit-log invariants.

    **Derivation Rules**:

    - `getEffector()` → `definition.effector` → resolves Effector
    - `getReceptor()` → `definition.receptor` → resolves Receptor
  end note

  Interaction --|> Ascription
  Interaction "0..*" --> "1" Effector : from
  Interaction "0..*" --> "1" Receptor : to

  ' ============================================================
  ' INTERFACE
  ' ============================================================

  class Interface {
    +getStructure(): Structure
    +getEffectors(): Effector[]
    +getReceptors(): Receptor[]
  }

  note bottom of Interface
    **Interface** — Exposed boundary of a Structure.

    **Concept Semantics**:

    - Declarative *exposure manifest*. Defines Structure's boundary
      surface by listing which Mechanism ports (Effectors/Receptors) are
      exposed for external coupling.
    - An Interface is **not** a Mechanism and has **no behavior** of its own.
      All behavior and realization lives in Mechanisms; Interfaces only define
      exposure.
    - Makes the boundary explicit and governable. Governance Norms can target an
      Interface directly (e.g., "all ports in this Interface must use mTLS").

    **Attribute Semantics**:

    - `structure`: the owning Structure. An Interface cannot exist without
      a Structure.
    - `effectors`/`receptors`: lists of referenced Effector/Receptor
      `id`s that declare which ports are exposed by this Interface.

    **Validation Rules**:

      - If `InterfaceArchetype.effectors`/`InterfaceArchetype.receptors` are
        present, they MUST reference ports (Effector/Receptor `id`) that belong
        to Mechanisms within the same Structure as the Interface's Structure.

    **State Rules**:

    - See `gsm-ascription-lifecycle` state machine diagram
      for valid transitions, preconditions, cascades,
      and audit-log invariants.

    **Derivation Rules**:

    - An external boundary view can be derived by enumerating the union of ports
      contained in all Interfaces.
    - An Interface's Structure can be derived by resolving its
      `InterfaceArchetype.effectors`/`InterfaceArchetype.receptors` to
      Effector/Receptor Ascriptions, then resolving each port to its
      owning Mechanism, then taking that Mechanism's
      `MechanismArchetype.structure`. (This relies on ports belonging
      exclusively to a single Mechanism, and a Mechanism belonging to a single
      Structure.)
    - `getStructure()` → derived (port → mechanism → structure chain)
    - `getEffectors()` → `definition.effectors` → resolves Effector[]
    - `getReceptors()` → `definition.receptors` → resolves Receptor[]

    **Usage Rules**:

    - Group ports by external exposure semantics (e.g., "admin", "monitoring",
      "public API").
    - Apply boundary-level governance Norms to Interfaces rather than individual
      ports when the constraint is uniform across all grouped ports, (AND)
      relative to the Interface itself.
  end note

  Interface --|> Ascription
  Interface "0..*" --> "1" Structure : constitutes
  Interface "0..*" --> "0..*" Effector : exposes
  Interface "0..*" --> "0..*" Receptor : exposes

  ' ============================================================
  ' ARCHETYPE
  ' ============================================================

  class Archetype {
    +getSchemaUri(): String
  }

  note bottom of Archetype
    **Archetype** — Named type definition (meta-model). Extends Ascription.

    **Concept Semantics**:

    - Defines the structure and semantics of the domain — the domain model /
      vocabulary. Archetype is the sole typed deliverable in the definition
      plane, replacing the former Object class.
    - Schemas enable informational extensibility for cross-domain, global
      systemic automatic reasoning to capture domain-specific knowledge and
      semantics.
    - Archetype extends Ascription, inheriting lifecycle management (status,
      version, statusTransitions). This makes Archetypes first-class
      governed artifacts — authorable, reviewable, activatable through the same
      governance process as all other Ascriptions.
    - **Self-typing (autopoietic bootstrap)**: since every Ascription references
      an Archetype, and Archetype IS an Ascription, Archetype instances
      reference an Archetype to type themselves. The root axiom is the
      **Archetype** — a built-in, pre-seeded Archetype whose
      `archetype` field references its own `id`. This is the single
      axiomatic seed from which the entire type system grows. All other
      Archetypes are typed by Archetype (or by a tenant Archetype
      that ultimately chains to it).
    - Archetype instances remain **semantically immutable**: once an Archetype
      revision is ACTIVE, its `definition.schemaUri` and `definition`
      MUST NOT change.
      Schema evolution is expressed by authoring a new Archetype revision (or a
      new Archetype entirely) — never by mutating the active one. The lifecycle
      inherited from Ascription governs when new Archetype definitions become
      active; immutability applies to the content of each revision.
    - Every Ascription instance references one Archetype.
    - Unified type construct for all structural and domain typing.
    - GSM base archetypes (sealed set): StructureArchetype, MechanismArchetype,
      InteractionArchetype, InterfaceArchetype, Archetype.
      EffectorArchetype and ReceptorArchetype are GSM-internal sealed archetypes
      for Mechanism ports (lifecycle-coupled, derived at compilation time) and
      MUST NOT be tenant-extended. DirectiveArchetype and NormArchetype are
      governance DNA archetypes (their schemas carry the governance grammar
      for Directive and Norm instances respectively). Base archetypes carry
      the `$gsm:sealed` marker in their JSON Schema.
    - Effectors and Receptors reference Archetypes directly to declare the
      type of information they emit/consume. The Archetype's
      `definition.schemaUri`
      determines the data structure.

    **Attribute Semantics**:

    - `schemaUri`: canonical URI for the JSON Schema document defining
      the structure of instances typed by this Archetype.

    **Validation Rules**:

    - `definition.schemaUri` MUST NOT be null.
    - `definition.schemaUri` MUST reference a valid JSON Schema
      (draft 2020-12+).
    - `definition.schemaUri` MUST be unique across all Archetypes.
    - `definition.schemaUri` MUST be immutable and version-pinned:
      dereferencing it MUST always return the same schema content over time.
      Mutable aliases such as "latest" (or any moving target) MUST be rejected
      by the definition-manager.
    - `definition.schemaUri` MUST point to a schema whose `allOf` chain
      ultimately roots at exactly one GSM base archetype schema. Intermediate
      tenant archetypes are permitted (depth-N chains) as long as all `allOf`
      paths converge to the same GSM base.
    - Schemas whose `allOf` chain does not root at a GSM base archetype MUST
      be rejected by the definition-manager.

    **Relational Consistency Rules**:

    - Any Ascription that references this Archetype MUST have
      `definition` compatible with the JSON Schema referenced by
      `definition.schemaUri`.

    **Derivation Rules**:

    - Base archetype classification is derived from the schema content
      (`allOf.$ref`), not from a separate field.
    - `getSchemaUri()` → `definition.schemaUri`

    **Usage Rules**:

    - Schema-declared inheritance: tenant archetypes declare which GSM base they
      extend via `allOf[{ "$ref": "<base-schema-uri>" }]` in their JSON Schema.
      The definition-manager derives the base archetype by walking the allOf
      chain to the GSM root — no separate field is needed on Archetype.
    - **Depth-N allOf chains (cross-cutting governance archetypes)**: tenant
      archetypes may extend other tenant archetypes (not only GSM bases
      directly), as long as all allOf paths converge to exactly one GSM base.
      This enables **cross-cutting governance**: a tenant defines intermediate
      "facet" archetypes (e.g., DataProtectionArchetype, PerformanceGoverned-
      Mechanism) that carry shared governance properties (e.g., gdprApplicable,
      maxLatencyMs). Multiple leaf archetypes compose these facets via allOf.
      A Directive can then reference a facet archetype as its qualifier-
      Id, and its Norms apply to ALL elements whose Archetype extends
      that facet — enabling cross-cutting NFR governance without per-Archetype
      duplication.
    - Tenant extensibility: tenants extend their Structure's vocabulary by
      declaring new Archetypes whose schema references a GSM base. E.g., a
      tenant creates Archetype "SecurityCheckMechanism" whose schema declares
      allOf[{ $ref: MechanismArchetype }] and adds { complianceFramework }
      alongside the base's `MechanismArchetype.rule`,
      `MechanismArchetype.ruleLanguage`, and `MechanismArchetype.function`.
    - Schema evolution MUST NOT mutate an existing `definition.schemaUri`
      target. If a schema must change, publish a new version at a new,
      version-pinned URI and author a new Archetype revision that references it.
      Existing Ascriptions remain pinned to the schema addressed by their
      Archetype's `definition.schemaUri`.

    **State Rules**:

    - See `gsm-ascription-lifecycle` state machine diagram
      for valid transitions, preconditions, cascades,
      and audit-log invariants.

    **Notes**:

    - **Bootstrap insertion**: the seed Archetype MUST be inserted by the
      definition-manager during initialization (store bootstrap) and may need to
      bypass normal “archetype must already exist” validation, because it is the
      entity that makes archetype resolution possible.
    - **Self-reference cycle is expected**: the seed Archetype's
      `archetypeId` references its own `id`. This produces an in-memory
      object graph cycle (`seed.archetype == seed`). This is correct and
      intentional.
    - **ORM/mapper recursion hazards**: ensure persistence mappings do NOT
      cascade persist/update through the `archetype` reference, and avoid eager
      recursive traversal.
    - **Serialization hazards**: any API/DTO that expands `archetype` objects
      recursively can loop on the seed. Prefer exposing `archetypeId` (and, at
      most, a single-level embedded archetype) or use cycle-aware serializers.
    - **Equality/logging hazards**: do not include the `archetype` object graph
      in `equals`/`hashCode`/`toString` implementations; use stable identifiers
      (`id`/`revisionId`) only.
  end note

  Archetype --|> Ascription
}

@enduml
